<subSubSection id="C36CDAD58D37FFF9B5EAFC6AFDB5FC20" box="[151,599,898,925]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="8BC9895E8D37FFF9B5EAFC6AFDB5FC20" blockId="15.[151,1437,898,1573]" box="[151,599,898,925]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">
<heading id="D0813E328D37FFF9B5EAFC6AFDB5FC20" bold="true" box="[151,599,898,925]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" reason="1">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B5EAFC6AFDB5FC20" bold="true" box="[151,599,898,925]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B5EAFC6AFE6FFC21" baseAuthorityName="Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[151,397,898,925]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="durbanensis">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B5EAFC6AFE6FFC21" bold="true" box="[151,397,898,925]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">Lysmata durbanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a valid species
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36CDAD58D37FFF9B5EAFC4FFEF2FBED" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BC9895E8D37FFF9B5EAFC4FFEF2FBED" blockId="15.[151,1437,898,1573]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">
Although data were limited, our analysis of the 
<specimenCount id="9D7042D78D37FFF9B7DEFC4FFCA0FC7D" box="[675,834,934,961]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" type="generic" typeStatus="syntypes">three syntypes</specimenCount>
of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B618FC4EFBE8FC7C" baseAuthorityName="Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[869,1034,934,960]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="durbanensis">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B618FC4EFBE8FC7C" box="[869,1034,934,960]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. durbanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
suggested it is not a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B5CAFC22FEFFFC58" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[183,285,971,996]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B5CAFC22FEFFFC58" box="[183,285,971,996]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, thus we formally resurrect it to full species status. While 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B6C8FC22FBBFFC58" baseAuthorityName="Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[949,1117,970,996]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="durbanensis">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B6C8FC22FBBFFC58" box="[949,1117,970,996]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. durbanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shared some morphological traits with 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B472FC06FE96FBB4" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[271,372,1007,1032]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B472FC06FE96FBB4" box="[271,372,1007,1032]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including a uniramous dorsal antennule, wide gap in the major chelae, and stylocerite exceeding the antennular peduncle (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE7F4AF8D37FFF9B49CFBFBFD5DFB90" author="Aguilar, R. &amp; Prakash, S. &amp; Ogburn, M. B. &amp; Lohan, K. M. P. &amp; MacDonald III, K. S. &amp; Driskell, A. C. &amp; Ahyong, S. T. &amp; Leray, M. &amp; McIlroy, S. E. &amp; Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A." box="[481,703,1042,1068]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" pagination="1" refId="ref16244" refString="Aguilar, R., Prakash, S., Ogburn, M. B., Lohan, K. M. P., MacDonald III, K. S., Driskell, A. C., Ahyong, S. T., Leray, M., McIlroy, S. E., Tuckey, T. D. &amp; Baeza, J. A. (2022) Unresolved taxonomy can confounds invasive species identification: the Lysmata vittata (Stimpson, 1860) (Decapoda: Caridea: Lysmatidae) species complex and recent introduction of Lysmata vittata sensu stricto in the western Atlantic. Journal of Crustacean Biology, 42 (1). https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / jcbiol / ruab 079" type="journal article" year="2022">
Aguilar 
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B73CFBFAFD99FB90" box="[577,635,1042,1068]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">et al.</emphasis>
2022
</bibRefCitation>
; present study), some divergences were noted in other important characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36CDAD58D37FFF9B5BAFBB2FB62F998" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BC9895E8D37FFF9B5BAFBB2FBB6FA05" blockId="15.[151,1437,898,1573]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">
In our examinations, of the 
<specimenCount id="9D7042D78D37FFF9B779FBB3FD44FBC9" box="[516,678,1114,1141]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" type="generic" typeStatus="syntypes">three syntypes</specimenCount>
two individuals possessed a long and slender rostrum, slightly exceeding the antennular peduncle, with dorsal and ventral teeth set very close to the tip, which was not seen in any of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B59CFB4AFEAAFB00" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[225,328,1187,1212]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B59CFB4AFEAAFB00" box="[225,328,1187,1212]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
examined in the present study. In the other individual, the rostrum was very short, not exceeding the first article of the antennular peduncle, but it appeared this may have been due to a mechanical deformity. We confirm the number of ventral spines in the dactyls of pereopods 3–5 as ranging from three to four, which is less than reported for 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B42AFAE6FE59FA94" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[343,443,1295,1320]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B42AFAE6FE59FA94" box="[343,443,1295,1320]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(5–6). Also, shrimps collected in 
<collectingCountry id="F361C9CE8D37FFF9B652FAE7FC5FFA94" box="[815,957,1294,1320]" name="South Africa" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">South Africa</collectingCountry>
tended to have higher number of spiniform setae on the propodus of pereopods 3–5 and more variable rostral teeth counts. Additionally, the disparate location of 
<collectingCountry id="F361C9CE8D37FFF9B5CAFABFFEA5FACC" box="[183,327,1366,1392]" name="South Africa" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">South Africa</collectingCountry>
in relation to the assumed native range of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B650FABEFC76FACC" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[813,916,1367,1392]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B650FABEFC76FACC" box="[813,916,1367,1392]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(temperate/subtropical northwestern Indo-Pacific, see below) is also suggestive that South African populations represent a different entity, though environmental conditions in the region are likely favorable to introductions of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B623FA76FC21FA04" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[862,963,1439,1464]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B623FA76FC21FA04" box="[862,963,1439,1464]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B684FA76FBAFFA04" authorityName="Laubenheimer &amp; Rhyne" authorityYear="2010" box="[1017,1101,1438,1464]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rauli">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B684FA76FBAFFA04" box="[1017,1101,1438,1464]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. rauli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC9895E8D37FFF9B5BAFA2BFB62F998" blockId="15.[151,1437,898,1573]" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">
There appears to be scarce data for and scant collections of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B61BFA2AFBEFFA60" baseAuthorityName="Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[870,1037,1474,1500]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="durbanensis">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B61BFA2AFBEFFA60" box="[870,1037,1474,1500]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. durbanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless, genetic examination of 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B5C8FA0EFEB9F9BC" baseAuthorityName="Stebbing" baseAuthorityYear="1921" box="[181,347,1510,1536]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="durbanensis">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B5C8FA0EFEB9F9BC" box="[181,347,1510,1536]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. durbanensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from across southern mainland Africa and outlying islands is required to resolve the phylogenetic relationship and distribution range of this species in the context of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C76F2DD8D37FFF9B6D1F9E2FBF3F998" baseAuthorityName="Stimpson" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[940,1041,1547,1572]" class="Malacostraca" family="Hippolytidae" genus="Lysmata" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="15" pageNumber="204" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vittata">
<emphasis id="B902554C8D37FFF9B6D1F9E2FBF3F998" box="[940,1041,1547,1572]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="204">L. vittata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
